Hardware Stock Management System — Complete Step Guide

🔧 BACKEND STEPS (Spring Boot — IntelliJ IDEA)

STEP 1 — Create Spring Boot Project

Go to https://start.spring.io
Select: Maven, Java 21, Spring Boot 3.x
Group: com.hardware | Artifact: hardware-management
Add dependencies: Spring Web, Spring Security, Spring Data JPA, PostgreSQL Driver, Lombok, Validation
Download and open in IntelliJ IDEA


STEP 2 — Add JWT Dependencies to pom.xml

Add jjwt-api, jjwt-impl, jjwt-jackson version 0.11.5 manually to pom.xml


STEP 3 — Setup PostgreSQL Database

Install PostgreSQL if not installed
Create database: hardware_db
Create user: hardware_user with password
Grant all privileges to that user


STEP 4 — Configure application.properties

Set datasource URL, username, password
Set JPA hibernate ddl-auto to update
Set JWT secret and expiration
Set server port to 8080


STEP 5 — Create Folder Structure
Create these packages inside com.hardware:

entity
repository
service and service/impl
controller
dto/request and dto/response
security
config
exception
util
mapper


STEP 6 — Create Enum Classes

Create Role enum → values: ADMIN, OWNER, CASHIER, STORE_KEEPER
Create PaymentType enum → values: CASH, CREDIT, CARD


STEP 7 — Create All Entity Classes
Create these one by one:

User entity → id, username, password, role, active
Category entity → id, name, description
Supplier entity → id, name, phone, email, address, creditBalance
Customer entity → id, name, phone, address, creditBalance
Product entity → id, name, sku, barcode, category, supplier, brand, unit, costPrice, sellingPrice, quantity, reorderLevel, active
Sale entity → id, customer, totalAmount, discount, paidAmount, paymentType, createdAt
SaleItem entity → id, sale, product, quantity, unitPrice, totalPrice
Purchase entity → id, supplier, totalAmount, note, createdAt
PurchaseItem entity → id, purchase, product, quantity, costPrice, totalPrice
StockAdjustment entity → id, product, adjustmentType, quantity, reason, createdAt


STEP 8 — Create All Repository Interfaces
Create JPA repository for each entity:

UserRepository → add findByUsername method
CategoryRepository
SupplierRepository
CustomerRepository
ProductRepository → add findBySku, findByBarcode, findByQuantityLessThanEqualReorderLevel methods
SaleRepository → add findByCreatedAtBetween method
SaleItemRepository
PurchaseRepository
PurchaseItemRepository
StockAdjustmentRepository


STEP 9 — Create DTO Classes
Request DTOs:

LoginRequest → username, password
RegisterRequest → username, password, role
CategoryRequest → name, description
SupplierRequest → name, phone, email, address
CustomerRequest → name, phone, address
ProductRequest → name, sku, barcode, categoryId, supplierId, brand, unit, costPrice, sellingPrice, reorderLevel
SaleRequest → customerId, paymentType, discount, paidAmount, list of items
SaleItemRequest → productId, quantity
PurchaseRequest → supplierId, note, list of items
PurchaseItemRequest → productId, quantity, costPrice
StockAdjustmentRequest → productId, adjustmentType, quantity, reason

Response DTOs:

AuthResponse → token, username, role
ProductResponse → all product fields including category name, supplier name
SaleResponse → all sale fields including items
PurchaseResponse → all purchase fields including items
LowStockResponse → product name, sku, quantity, reorderLevel
DashboardResponse → todaySales, totalProducts, lowStockCount, totalCustomers


STEP 10 — Create JWT Security Classes

JwtUtil class → generateToken, extractUsername, validateToken methods
JwtAuthFilter class → extends OncePerRequestFilter, reads Authorization header, validates token
CustomUserDetailsService class → implements UserDetailsService, loads user by username from DB


STEP 11 — Create Security Configuration

SecurityConfig class → disable CSRF, permit /api/auth/**, protect all other routes, add JwtAuthFilter, set stateless session, define PasswordEncoder bean, define AuthenticationManager bean


STEP 12 — Create Exception Classes

ResourceNotFoundException → extends RuntimeException
InsufficientStockException → extends RuntimeException
DuplicateEntryException → extends RuntimeException
GlobalExceptionHandler class → annotated with @RestControllerAdvice, handles all above exceptions and returns proper error responses


STEP 13 — Create Service Layer
AuthService:

login method → authenticate user, generate JWT token, return AuthResponse
register method → encode password, save user

CategoryService:

getAllCategories
getCategoryById
createCategory
updateCategory
deleteCategory

SupplierService:

getAllSuppliers
getSupplierById
createSupplier
updateSupplier
deleteSupplier

CustomerService:

getAllCustomers
getCustomerById
createCustomer
updateCustomer
getCustomersWithCredit

ProductService:

getAllProducts
getProductById
getProductByBarcode
createProduct
updateProduct
deleteProduct
getLowStockProducts
updateStock (internal method used by sale and purchase services)

PurchaseService (GRN):

createPurchase → save purchase, save purchase items, increase product stock quantity

SaleService:

createSale → validate stock, save sale, save sale items, decrease product stock quantity, handle credit customer balance
getSaleById
getSalesByDateRange

StockAdjustmentService:

createAdjustment → increase or decrease stock based on adjustmentType

ReportService:

getDashboardSummary
getDailySalesReport
getMonthlySalesReport
getLowStockReport
getTopSellingProducts


STEP 14 — Create Controller Layer

AuthController → POST /api/auth/login, POST /api/auth/register
CategoryController → GET, POST, PUT, DELETE /api/categories
SupplierController → GET, POST, PUT, DELETE /api/suppliers
CustomerController → GET, POST, PUT, DELETE /api/customers, GET /api/customers/credit
ProductController → GET, POST, PUT, DELETE /api/products, GET /api/products/low-stock, GET /api/products/barcode/{barcode}
PurchaseController → GET, POST /api/purchases
SaleController → GET, POST /api/sales, GET /api/sales/report
StockAdjustmentController → POST /api/stock-adjustments
ReportController → GET /api/reports/dashboard, GET /api/reports/daily, GET /api/reports/monthly, GET /api/reports/top-products


STEP 15 — Add CORS Configuration

Create CorsConfig class → allow all origins (for development), allow all headers and methods


STEP 16 — Add Initial Data Seeder

Create DataSeeder class → implements ApplicationRunner
On startup → check if admin user exists, if not create default admin user with encoded password


STEP 17 — Test Backend with Postman
Test in this order:

Register admin user
Login and get JWT token
Create a category
Create a supplier
Create a product
Create a purchase (GRN) — stock should increase
Create a sale — stock should decrease
Check low stock products
Check dashboard report



